<H3> <TI>   Italy, Germany Proposed for UN Security Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italy, Germany Proposed for UN Security Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0106094194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0809 GMT 1 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0106094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy, Germany To Serve Two Years </F>
on Security Council"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) New York, June 1 -- Italy and Germany have 
been put forward by the Western nations to take over, January 1, 
from New Zealand and Spain for a two-year stint among the UN 
Security Council's 10 nonpermanent members, an Italian spokesman 
confirmed here this morning. The candidacy was made after the 
withdrawal of Ireland, Greece, and Sweden, which said it will be 
seeking the job for 1997-98. 
  The appointment is expected to be approved by the UN General 
Assembly in October. 
  The Security Council has five permanent members -- the 
United 
States, Russia, China, Britain and France -- and 10 nonpermanent 
members rotating every two years. 
  Italy and Germany are among the countries which have 
repeatedly requested an enlargement of the Council. 

</TEXT>

