<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Calls Lifting Bosnian Embargo `Disastrous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Calls Lifting Bosnian Embargo `Disastrous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0206133294 Paris LE FIGARO in French 2 Jun 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> BR0206133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Anne Fulda: "Bosnia: Juppe Asserts His </F>
Convictions"] 
  [Excerpts] Montpellier -- After the big show of support by 
the UDF [French Democratic Union] in Lyons on Tuesday [31 May], 
Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, who is secretary general of the 
RPR [Rally for the Republic], came to Montpellier yesterday to 
encourage the "Union" list of the majority. Flanked by Philippe 
Vasseur, the general secretary of the Republican Party [PR] and 
a deputy for the Pas-de-Calais region; Dominique Baudis; and 
Jacques Blanc, president of the regional council of 
Languedoc-Roussillon (PR), the minister's speech focused on 
three main subjects: the challenge of unemployment, the 
challenge of European Union [EU] enlargement, and the challenge 
of Yugoslavia. 
  Alain Juppe devoted the main part of his speech to this last 
subject, in which he takes a particular interest, especially 
after the attacks he endured recently by the still-born "Europe 
Begins in Sarajevo" list. [passage omitted] 
  Alain Juppe clearly stated his position on the lifting of 
the 
arms embargo on the Muslims, a measure requested by the 
"intellectuals' list" and by [Socialist Party Secretary 
General] Michel Rocard. He admitted that "once the 
international community had accepted the birth of new 
independent states, maintaining this embargo perhaps was a 
mistake, or rather a case of injustice." Nevertheless, he 
argued, "today the situation is radically different.... In view 
of the operational constraints imposed on our forces, the idea 
of lifting the arms embargo is simplistic.... I believe it 
would be disastrous." The minister hammered the point home: 
"If certain countries were to disregard the embargo, Russia 
would take the side of the Serbs. The war would spread 
immediately and the Bosnians would be condemned to military 
defeat even more certainly than before." 
  Alain Juppe concluded by saying: "Lifting the embargo is 
certainly a mobilizing slogan, but it would make things worse. 
This is why I am proposing the exact opposite step: Instead of 
increasing the number of heavy weapons in Bosnia, we must reduce 
their number; instead of giving weapons to those who do not have 
as many, we must take away weapons from those who have too 
many." He added: "Do those people in France and elsewhere who 
are encouraging the fighting to continue realize that they are 
likely to cause misfortune to people whose cause they think they 
are defending?" 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42476 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu107_i_94002" </HT>


