<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Technical Fault Scrubs Launch </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Technical Fault Scrubs Launch </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0406093194 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0800 
GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ariane rocket which was expected to place three 
satellites into orbit at 0700 GMT today did not launch as 
scheduled from the Kourou base in Guyana. Bruno Rougier reports. 
  [Rougier] Ariane was not launched because the arm which was 
supposed to feed the rocket with hydrogen did not open. The 
rocket is held by two arms that open five seconds before launch. 
Unlike the hydrogen arm, the oxygen arm opened. The reason is 
still unknown, but there is one key thing I must emphasize: the 
launcher is not in danger at the moment. 
  Technicians are now busy cleaning the two tanks. The 
hydrogen tank will normally be emptied by the attached tube. As 
for the oxygen tank, a purification system will likely be used; 
this should take several hours. Following this technician 
should know why the arm failed to open. In addition, the 
launching system will be examined to replace some spare parts 
and repair some connections. Ariane Space management has refused 
to say when a new launch will take place. According to experts 
I met this morning, the delay could take a week. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

