<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Announces Tough Austerity Course for 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Announces Tough Austerity Course for 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306123494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1136 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- The welfare state has reached 
the limits of its capacity, according to Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
The future of Germany cannot be dealt with using the principles 
of "a leisure park," Kohl said today addressing the CDU/CSU 
[Christian Democrat Union/Christian Social Union] industrial 
committee in Munich. 
  The CDU leader announced a "tough austerity course" for 
1995. 
The watchword in the future must be "rethinking, not 
redistribution." Kohl said that the cornerstones of the tax 
program for the next period in office are to be submitted in the 
near future. Under this program, a cut in business tax is 
proposed to protect Germany as an investment location. 
  In view of the increasing competition on world markets, the 
German economy can no longer allow itself to stay in second-last 
place among the EU countries in terms of machinery utilization 
times, Kohl said. The chancellor noted "encouraging signs" in 
the progress of the economy despite the existing problems. He 
highlighted the recent "sensible wage agreements," the cuts in 
key interest rates by the German Bundesbank, and the low 
inflation rate. He said that the major challenge is 
unemployment. To preserve Germany as an investment location, 
high-performance elites will have to be called for and accepted 
again. 

</TEXT>

