<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cavaco Silva on Angola, Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106195594 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
1600 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106195594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Cavaco Silva today visited the 
National Defense Institute and delivered an interesting lecture 
to the graduates on the state of the economy, the European 
Union, and foreign policy. More details from Paulo Barbosa: 
  [Barbosa] [passage omitted] The prime minister spoke about 
foreign policy and Angola: 
  [Begin Cavaco Silva recording] We continue to follow closely 
the Lusaka peace talks and to support the UN envoy's efforts. 
These efforts are aimed at reaching an agreement that may allow 
the existence of a fair and long-lasting peace process in that 
tormented country. 
  The situation in Angola is truly tragic: A lot more people 
are dying in Angola than in the Bosnian conflict. Therefore, it 
is imperative that the international community does not abandon 
Angola, that it keeps showing an interest in the ongoing 
negotiations, and that it shows its readiness -- in case an 
agreement is reached -- to give the necessary assurances for its 
compliance, namely the availabilty on the ground of a UN peace 
force. 
  We have not yet signed a military cooperation agreement with 
Angola because of the situation of armed conflict that still 
coexists with the endless Lusaka peace negotiations. [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

