<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister on UN Report, Visit to Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister on UN Report, Visit to Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0406195394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1900 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0406195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Cyprus Government believes that, after the 
Butrus-Ghali report, the neutralization of the Turkish side's 
lack of political will is feasible if negotiations with the 
European Union [EU] for Cyprus' accession are immediately 
opened. In a statement to CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting 
Corporation], Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said that, 
once a decision is made to begin the negotiations, the Turkish 
side will find itself facing a dilemma. 
  Referring to the visit he will begin in Moscow tomorrow, Mr. 
Mikhailidhis described it as important, because it will take 
place immediately after the Butrus-Ghali report, which includes 
some of the suggestions submitted by the Russians. Responding 
to a question, Mr. Mikhailidhis said that the time has come for 
Russian intervention in the process to promote a Cyprus 
solution. He also noted that Russia plays an important role and 
added that at his talks in Moscow they will examine the options 
proposed by the UN Secretary General in his report and will also 
discuss the Russian proposals toward promoting a Cyprus solution. 
  The foreign minister further said that the consultations, 
which the Secretary General proposes in his report on 
alternative ways to promote the Cyprus issue, should be based on 
the finding of the lack of political will on the Turkish side. 
  Referring to his meetings with the ambassadors of the five 
permanent members of the Security Council, Mr. Mikhailidhis said 
that some people continue to believe that there are 
possibilities in the confidence-building measures. Mr. 
Mikhailidhis added that he stressed to the ambassadors that it 
would be a tactical error to ignore the findings in the 
Butrus-Ghali report, which he described as a landmark. 

</TEXT>

