<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Talks on FYROM Convene in Athens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Talks on FYROM Convene in Athens </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    U.S. Presidential Envoy Arrives </H4>

<F P=102> NC0606102594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0900 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0606102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Matthew Nimetz, the U.S. presidential envoy on the 
issue of Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM], arrived in Athens a short while ago for talks 
with the Greek Government. He will meet Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias at 1930 today. 
  Nimetz said he is not bringing any specific new proposals on 
the issue of Skopje, but he appeared optimistic about the 
mediation to smooth Greek-Skopjean relations. He left open the 
possibility of meeting Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, adding 
that such a meeting would depend on his talks with the foreign 
minister this afternoon. 
  In a major article yesterday, THE WASHINGTON POST predicted 
a 
Greek-Skopjean compromise, stressing that Skopje had wrongly 
exceeded beyond its authority in adopting historical and 
nationalistic symbols. The article says that with its relaxed 
diplomacy, the United States allowed the fire to spread, thus 
forcing Athens to harden its stance in the dispute with Skopje. 
According to the report, Washington's role is considered 
strained due to the stationing of 600 peacekeepers in Skopje, 
who could be the cause of confrontations throughout the Balkans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

