<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Responds to Tirana on EU Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Responds to Tirana on EU Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0606150794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0606150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Replying to an Albanian Foreign Ministry statement 
made yesterday accusing Greece of blocking European Union [EU] 
aid, thus punishing Albania and the Greek minority, Foreign 
Ministry Spokesman Konstandinos Bikas said Greece is following 
an open-door policy toward Albania. He said the Greek 
Government wants good relations with Albania, adding that it 
respects Albania's territorial integrity. He stressed, however, 
that the cornerstone of good bilateral relations is respect for 
the human and minority rights. 
  Referring to Albanian-EU relations, the Foreign Ministry 
spokesman said Greece is obliged to tell Albania that its 
relations with the EU depend on respect for human rights. Bikas 
recalled that 350,000 Albanians live and work in Greece, thus 
strengthening the Albanian economy with $300 million a year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

