<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Begins Talks on Karkuk-Yumurtalik Pipeline </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Begins Talks on Karkuk-Yumurtalik Pipeline </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Prime Minister Comments </H4>

<F P=102> TA0506115494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1000 
GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0506115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has said that it will 
be possible very soon to pump out the oil in the 
Karkuk-Yumurtalik for restoration purposes. 
  Answering reporters' questions at the prime minister's 
residence, Ciller said they have been trying to explain to the 
world why it is necessary to pump the oil out of the 
Karkuk-Yumurtalik oil pipeline in spite of the embargo imposed 
on Iraq, and added: A unity of understanding has been 
developing in world public opinion in recent months. 
  Stressing that the oil pipeline should be considered one of 
Turkey's investments, Ciller said: The embargo is not imposed 
on Turkey. There is oil in the pipeline and some of that oil 
belongs to us. We have to pump out this oil in order to repair, 
restore, and conduct maintenance work, and we are explaining 
this to the world. In my last visit to the United States, I 
discussed this issue. In the past, the issue was being assessed 
within the framework of the embargo. I see a slightly different 
approach developing now. I am very hopeful on this issue, and I 
believe it will be possible to conduct repair work in the near 
future. 
  In answer to a question, Ciller said discussions on the oil 
pipeline are being conducted in various circles, including with 
the UN secretary general, and added: The world has become a 
smaller place. Turkey has led the world in certain issues. We 
sided with the human rights issue when Iraq was the aggressor. 
That decision was right then, but the decision on the oil 
pipeline is the right one for now. The embargo is not imposed 
on us, but it is destroying our investments -- millions of 
dollars of investments. We cannot allow these investments to be 
wasted. The world also should not allow this. I think we have 
explained our situation satisfactorily. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42582 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu108_q_94005" </HT>


