<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42583 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu108_q_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Begins Talks on Karkuk-Yumurtalik Pipeline </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Begins Talks on Karkuk-Yumurtalik Pipeline </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Cetin: Talks To Continue </H4>

<F P=102> TA0606065794 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
2000 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0606065794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has said that there 
is no difference of opinion between Turkey and the UN Security 
Council members about eliminating the losses incurred from the 
oil sitting in the Karkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline for the past four 
years. He stressed, however, that it appears that the operation 
to rescue the pipeline cannot be carried out without regard for 
the embargo on Iraq or by ignoring the United Nations. 
  Cetin was replying to questions at Ankara's Esenboga Airport 
after seeing off the Thai foreign minister. Cetin pointed out 
that the problem does not concern the United Nations alone and 
that the Iraqi side should not be ignored. He added: This must 
be done on common ground with Iraq. As far as we understand, 
Iraq will not export the oil and no resources will be 
transferred to Iraq. Consequently, we are continuing to explain 
that this is a special operation. After our contacts with the 
United Nations, we will contact Iraq once again if necessary and 
try to reach a solution for the issue. 
  Replying to a question, Cetin said that no conclusion has 
been reached during the talks in New York about whether Iraq's 
share of the revenues from the oil in the pipeline will be 
placed in the UN compensation account. He said: In light of 
these negotiations, we will either say that an agreement has 
been reached and act accordingly, or we will say that the 
differences of opinion will be discussed again. In other words, 
the process is under way. I believe that it will continue. 
Turkey is right. I do not believe there is a way back from 
here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

