<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Council Meets; Kliridhis Hopeful of Consensus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Council Meets; Kliridhis Hopeful of Consensus </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0306194994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0306194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis today expressed the 
conviction that all the right conditions exist for the National 
Council to reach a consensus regarding the future direction of 
the Cyprus issue, in light of the Butrus-Ghali report. Speaking 
after the meeting of the National Council this morning, 
President Kliridhis said that the Greek Cypriot side should not 
celebrate about the Butrus-Ghali report because a report is not 
a solution of the Cyprus issue. However, he described the UN 
secretary general's position -- that efforts to solve the Cyprus 
issue have gone on for years but have not produced results 
because the Turkish side does not have the political will -- as 
very positive. 
  President Kliridhis said that during the National Council 
meeting today, there was a very good discussion which will 
continue Wednesday [8 June] after the political parties discuss 
the whole issue in their respective committees. The president 
said that during the meeting, he made suggestions to the parties 
and then a discussion followed. He said that before we go to 
Athens for discussions, we will decide what line we will follow, 
but we will not announce any decisions that we make here. Asked 
when the political leadership will go to Athens for talks, the 
president said the trip would take place after the 12 June 
elections for European Parliament. It should be noted that 
immediately following the National Council meeting, the 
president received Greek Ambassador Alexandros Sandhis, whom he 
briefed about the Council's meeting. 
  The National Council meeting was attended by Ioannis Matsis 
and Alekos Markidhis on behalf of the Democratic Rally [DISI], 
Dhimitrios Khristofias and Andreas Khristou on behalf of AKEL 
[Restorative Party of the Working People], Spiros Kiprianou and 
Tasos Papadhopoulos on behalf of DIKO [Democratic Party], and 
Vasos Lissaridhis and Takis Khatzidhimistriou on behalf of EDEK 
[United Democratic Union of Cyprus]. The meeting was also 
attended by House of Representatives President Alexis Galanos, 
Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis, and Ioannis Kasoulidhis, 
deputy minister to President Pandelis Kouros and government 
spokesman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

