<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: CD, Christian People's Party Lose Seats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: CD, Christian People's Party Lose Seats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0306120094 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG in Danish 
29 May 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0306120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG </F>
<F P=105>  Danish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Louise Fleischer report: "Radical Liberals Picking Up </F>
Voters"] 
  [Text] The government would lose a total of 16 seats if 
there were an election now. Both the Christian People's Party 
and the Center Democrats [CD] would disappear from the Folketing. 
  While both the CD and the Christian People's Party are 
likely 
to be completely erased from the Folketing, the Radical Liberals 
would make marked gains if there were a Folketing election now. 
  The party would have 10 seats against its current 7. This is 
shown by an opinion poll that Gallup has carried out for 
BERLINGSKE TIDENDE. 
  "I believe that people have begun to form a picture of us as 
a stable party. And there can be no doubt that our voters are 
well satisfied that we are involved in government cooperation," 
Radical Liberal Folketing group chairman Jens Bilgrav-Nielsen 
said. "The fact that we have three ministers who are very 
visible and who are responsible for areas that are important to 
Radical Liberals is probably also of significance. And the fact 
that we are demonstrating our opposition to the Oresund bridge 
may also have a role to play in this context. 
  ``While I do not think that individual issues persuade 
people 
to vote for the Radical Liberals, more than 50 percent of the 
population think that the idea of that bridge is stupid,'' said 
Jens Bilgrav-Nielsen, who himself is one of the bridge's most 
determined opponents. 
  At present the Radical Liberals seem to be the only party to 
have benefited from involvement in government. The government 
looks as if it will lose a total of 16 seats. The Social 
Democrats will lose 6 compared with the last election, while 
neither the Christian People's Party nor the CD are able to 
attract enough votes to stay above the threshold for 
representation in the Folketing. 
  The Liberal Party has lost two seats since the last Gallup 
poll in April, but the party is still on course for a major 
success in comparison with the 1990 election. Uffe 
Ellemann-Jensen would enter the Folketing with 49 seats behind 
him. 


