<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Not To Send More Troops to Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0606142194 Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN in Dutch 4 Jun 94 p 
6 </F>

<F P=103> BR0606142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "No Additional Blue Helmets To </F>
Baranja"] 
  [Text] After some hesitation about increasing the number of 
Belgian military personnel in Baranja (Croatia) by several 
dozen, the government decided on Friday [3 June] to take another 
path. For more than two years, a reinforced Belgian UN battalion 
has been stationed in Serb-occupied Baranja. In late February, 
at the height of the tension surrounding Sarajevo, one armored 
combat company, however, was assigned to go and back up the UN 
troops in Bosnia posthaste. This move meant that a large 
proportion of the protection for the Baranja detachment (BELBAT) 
was lost. After the experience in Rwanda, it was decided to 
reinforce this detachment with extra armored vehicles. On 
Friday, it was decided not to send new men or equipment there. 
The general staff were ordered by the UN senior command to 
investigate how the Belgian combat company in Bosnia could be 
reincorporated into BELBAT. Belgium is, however, temporarily 
keeping its transport and engineering company in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

