<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU To Study Legislation on Economic Initiatives </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU To Study Legislation on Economic Initiatives </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0606171794 Paris AFP in English 1616 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0606171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luxembourg, June 6 (AFP) -- The European Union [EU] 
will set up a group of experts to study slimming down 
legislation holding back private initiatives, economic 
development and job creation, German Finance Minister Theo 
Waigel announced in Luxembourg on Monday [6 June]. 
  EU finance ministers, meeting here, approved establishment 
of 
such a group, which will make proposals for simplifying EU and 
national legislation, he said. 
  German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt had sent a 
memorandum to other EU countries suggesting creation of a panel 
of experts to study deregulation. 
  But European Commission President Jacques Delors strongly 
opposed the idea at a finance ministers' meeting in Brussels on 
May 16, giving rise to a lively debate between Delors and the 
German ministers -- backed by British Chancellor of the 
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke. 
  Germany wanted the experts group to be fully independent of 
the Commission --but Delors thought that would mean entrusting 
outside experts with decision-making power. The EU finally 
decided that the experts could belong to the Commission or be 
independent, and the group will meet under Commission aegis. 
  Its first conclusions are expected some time next year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

