<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   German, Spanish Delegations Discuss Current Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    German, Spanish Delegations Discuss Current Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606193894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1815 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Schwerin (DDP/ADN) -- Germany and Spain have agreed 
on several concrete steps for expanding bilateral relations and 
European cooperation. Government spokesman Dieter Vogel said 
this on Monday [6 June] evening in Schwerin, commenting on the 
results of German-Spanish consultations. 
  It was agreed at the talks between the two states' heads of 
government, Helmut Kohl and Felipe Gonzalez, that there will be 
careful preparation for and bilateral coordination of the 
meeting of the European Union [EU] council in Corfu in June. 
There should also be closer cooperation among France, Germany, 
and Spain regarding the EU presidency. 
  The representatives of the two countries' Foreign Ministries 
agreed to press for the accession of four states of Central and 
East Europe to the EU. The representatives of the Interior 
Ministries agreed, within the framework of the first government 
consultations to take place in eastern Germany, to develop and 
pursue a joint asylum and refugee policy within the EU. The 
work of the European headquarters for criminal investigation 
(Europol) should also be "pushed forward" and its activities 
extended to terrorism. 
  Apart from relations between Russia and NATO, the talks 
between Defence Minister Ruehe and his Spanish counterpart were 
dominated by Spain's entry into the Eurocorps and the 
development of a joint European military transport aircraft, the 
government spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

