<H3> <TI>   Eisele Nominated for Senior UN Post </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Eisele Nominated for Senior UN Post </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0606170694 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 6 Jun 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU0606170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "German General"] </F>
  [Text] The Federal Government has nominated Major General 
Manfred Eisele, 56, for a top position with the United Nations. 
As an "assistant secretary general," he will control the 
worldwide missions of blue-helmeted peace troops from UN 
headquarters in New York. The nomination for the new leading 
position prior to the ruling of the Federal Constitutional Court 
on the admissibility of out-of-area missions of the Bundeswehr 
led to controversies in Bonn between the Foreign Ministry, the 
Defense Ministry, and the Chancellor's Office. In the 
mid-1980's, Eisele, who was the commander of the Hamburg Armored 
Infantry Brigade No. 17, discredited himself with his superiors. 
TV reporters had asked recruits of his brigade what they would 
do in the so-called defense case. The general had to defend 
himself for the almost unanimous reply "clear off." When 
Minister Volker Ruehe took office in 1992, Eisele was replaced 
prematurely after no more than 12 months as the chief of the 
Military Policy Department in the Defense Ministry, because he 
was considered to be overtaxed. Since early April, he has been 
chief of the Bonn Bundeswehr Office. In Defense Ministry 
jargon, this authority has been derisively called the "soldiers' 
cemetery," because it is where officers whom the Defense 
Ministry wants to get rid of are transferred. Eisele went to New 
York last week for an interview at the United Nations. 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali must yet confirm the 
nomination for the influential post, which he wants to fill with 
a German. 

</TEXT>

