<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Wants Uniform EU Laws on Right Extremists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Wants Uniform EU Laws on Right Extremists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706112694 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 7 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0706112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Justice Minister Sabine </F>
Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger by Alexandra Foederl-Schmid in 
Rostock; date not given: "Uniform Laws Against Right-Wing 
Extremists"] 
  [Text] [Foederl-Schmid] Violent clashes took place on the 
occasion of the friendly soccer match between Austria and 
Germany a few days ago. In your opinion, what should be done 
against it? 
  [Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger] I deplore very much that such 
friendly matches are overshadowed by such acts of violence. Of 
course, one has to take consistent action against it, as has 
also been done in Germany. This was partly done by calling in 
the Public Prosecutor's Office. Of course, it is bad that 
extreme right-wing motives also played a role in Austria. This 
makes it clear how important it is that Germany and Austria take 
joint action against this development. 
  [Foederl-Schmid] What is the joint course of action against 
right-wing extremists supposed to be like? 
  [Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger] It is very important that we 
cooperate with the police and judicial authorities and exchange 
information. We have to sit back and watch cross-border 
contacts developing increasingly frequently, not only with 
Austria, but also with other European neighbors. We have to pay 
even more attention to it than before. For me the German EU 
[European Union] presidency will be an opportunity to try to 
adjust the different criminal law provisions in the individual 
European member states, that is, no European criminal law, but 
the attempt to work toward a more uniform level than at present. 
  [Foederl-Schmid] Can you give an example? 
  [Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger] In some European member 
states, it is currently not forbidden to produce Nazi symbols or 
to print National Socialist ideas in newspapers. These products 
enter the German market. In our country this is punishable, but 
we do reach the people who produced it. They are in countries 
where production is not punishable. Here one should try to 
adjust the law among the states. 
  [Foederl-Schmid] Are the Austrian and the German judicial 
authorities already cooperating now? 
  [Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger] We have close contacts. Only 
a few days ago, talks among my state secretary, my Austrian 
colleagues, and experts from the Justice Ministry took place. 
The questions that have just been mentioned were also discussed 
there. 
  [Foederl-Schmid] Can Austria be an example with its law 
against right-wing extremism? For example, the Auschwitz lie 
has been punishable for a relatively long time. 
  [Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger] We are also planning to make 
the denial of the Holocaust punishable. According to my 
assessment, the provisions in Germany and Austria are similar. 
It will certainly be good if we also follow a joint course in 
the EU and try to convince others of it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

