<H3> <TI>   Navy Chief Notes EU Membership Responsibilities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Navy Chief Notes EU Membership Responsibilities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94EN0345A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 9 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> 94EN0345A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Navy Demands More Vessels"] </F>
  [Text] The planned expansion of the territorial waters 
means that the Navy will call for considerably more resources. 
Rear Admiral Sakari Visa, the naval commander, indicated in an 
interview on Sunday [8 May] with TURUN SANOMAT that the new sea 
regions cannot be monitored effectively without additional 
resources. 
  According to Visa, the Navy's greatest need is for four or 
five new patrol boats and new fixed materiel. Finland must also 
acquire submarines. Visa believes that if Finland had a 
submarine flotilla of its own, it would be much easier to patrol 
sea areas and to raise the threshold for border violations. 
  But submarines are not at the top of the Navy's wish list, 
according to Visa. 
  Several weeks ago, in one of its evening sessions, the 
government decided in principle to expand the territorial 
boundary from the present 4 nautical miles to 12 nautical miles. 
According to plans, the parliament will be presented with a 
proposal on this matter as early as this month. Rear Adm. Visa 
points out that, despite this decision, the Navy has not been 
promised any more ships or personnel. In the TURUN SANOMAT 
interview, Visa also pointed out that Finnish membership in the 
European Union [EU] would place new demands on border monitoring 
and on the defense in general, since Finland's boundaries would 
then be the outer boundaries of the Union, as well. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

