  [Text] Matthew Nimetz, the U.S. President's special envoy 
on Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM], 
came to Athens today with no new ideas. The U.S. official had a 
meeting with Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias this evening 
that lasted for one and a half hours. Nimetz will go to Skopje 
tomorrow. 
  [Begin Foivos Karzis recording] Foreign Minister Papoulias 
and U.S. Presidential Envoy Nimetz had a meeting of a rather 
exploratory nature this evening, in view of the new round of 
contacts in New York. Nimetz confirmed that he was not bringing 
any new ideas. On the other hand, Papoulias expressed the view 
that the meeting between Nimetz and [FYROM President] Kiro 
Gligorov tomorrow in Skopje will be important. The possibility 
that Nimetz will return to Athens after his contacts with the 
Skopjean leadership remains open. In that case, Papoulias said, 
we will have a clearer picture of the situation. 
  Papoulias expressed the hope that the meetings he and [FYROM 
Foreign Minister] Stevo Crvenkovski will have with Cyrus Vance 
and Nimetz in New York between 14 and 17 June will be the final 
round of deliberations on the Skopje issue. In any case, it is 
indicative that Nimetz's agenda this time was clearly more 
limited, as he did not meet with Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou or Yeoryios Papandreou, deputy foreign minister in 
charge of Greek-American relations. This morning, Papoulias 
briefed President Konstandinos Karamanlis on the developments in 
the national issues and described the scenarios of a triple name 
for Skopje as unrealistic. [end recording] 

