<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thai Foreign Minister Sunsiri Makes Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Thai Foreign Minister Sunsiri Makes Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Concludes Ankara Contacts </H4>

<F P=102> TA0506184594 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0506184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Thai Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri has concluded 
his Ankara contacts and left for Istanbul. He was seen off at 
Esenboga Airport by Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin. In an 
airport statement, Cetin said that hopeful decisions on 
promoting bilateral relations were made during Sunsiri's visit. 
Recalling that the Turkish Airlines has three weekly flights to 
Bangkok, Cetin added that they have agreed to increase the 
number of flights. He noted that decisions have also been 
reached to bring together the private sectors, especially the 
contracting sectors, of the two countries and to continue 
high-level visits within this framework. Cetin said: 
  [Begin Cetin recording] We believe that if Turkish manpower, 
development potential, and experience are combined with the 
technology, the rapid development rate, and market quests of 
Asian countries, both sides can benefit from the results. No 
doubt, within this framework, Thailand is an important country 
in its region. Our cooperation with Thailand will greatly 
contribute to Turkey's cooperation with that region. [end 
recording] 
  Sunsiri said his visit has been beneficial for bilateral 
relations. He added that during his contacts an agreement was 
also reached to hold the Turkish-Thai joint economic committee 
meeting in Turkey this year. Sunsiri will leave Turkey this 
evening. 

</TEXT>

