<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin News Conference on Medical Treatment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin News Conference on Medical Treatment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706130894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1234 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mainz (DDP/ADN) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin is presently on a private visit to Mainz to have a 
kidney stone complaint examined. His Moscow doctors advised him 
to obtain a second opinion in Germany, Chernomyrdin told a news 
conference in Mainz today. Treatment for the illness, from 
which he has suffered for several years, could not be put off 
any longer. Chernomyrdin said the kidney complaint "bothers" 
him, but it does not impair his work in any way. The prime 
minister announced that the treatment will presumably begin in 
Mainz and be continued in Moscow. A long stay in Germany is not 
planned: "I may fly back before Friday [10 June]," Chernomyrdin 
said. 
  Rudolf Hohenfellner, the doctor treating Chernomyrdin at the 
Johannes Gutenberg University Clinic in Mainz, confirmed that 
Chernomyrdin is not suffering from any other illnesses. "His 
state of health is actually excellent," Hohenfellner said. A 
decision on treatment will not be made until the final diagnosis 
has been obtained this afternoon, the doctor said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

