  [Text] Munich (DPA) -- Chancellor Helmut Kohl (Christian 
Democratic Union) sticks to his view that a German head of 
government should not attend the celebrations of the former 
Allies in commemoration of the landing in Normandy. "This is 
not the day on which the German chancellor would be in the right 
place there," Kohl said in Munich on Friday [3 June]. The 
meeting in northern France next Monday will be attended by heads 
of state and government of the former anti-Hitler coalition. 
  As an example of how this occasion should make "one look 
forward," Kohl cited the meeting that he and French President 
Francois Mitterrand have agreed to hold in Heidelberg two days 
later. There "a festival of friendship will take place with 
thousands of young people," he said at a lecture at the 
Christian Democratic Union's Economic Advisory Council. 

