<H3> <TI>   Minister Appeals to Clinton To Ease Iraq Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Appeals to Clinton To Ease Iraq Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0306142094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1345 GMT 3 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0306142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Iraq: Italian Health Minister </F>
Appeals to Clinton"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, June 3 -- The plight of Iraq, which is 
without access to adequate medical supplies due to an 
international embargo, was presented to United States President 
Bill Clinton in a letter from Health Minister Raffaele Costa, 
Friday [3 June]. 
  "More than three years after the end of the war in that 
country, which is now isolated and forgotten, tens of thousands 
of people, including many children, are in a serious condition 
but receive little health care because of insufficient 
medicines," wrote Costa in a letter delivered to the U.S. 
embassy here. 
  "Thousands of people have died or are dying of malnutrition, 
in epidemics, or as a result of the war," said Costa who added 
that humanitarian organisations and Italian President Oscar 
Luigi Scalfaro were amongst those who have pressed him to act to 
better the lot of suffering Iraqis. 
  According to the health minister "the government there is 
prepared to pay (for medical supplies) but cannot receive them, 
or receives them after a long delay, due to the extremely strict 
controls and major obstacles imposed by the embargo." 

</TEXT>

