<H3> <TI>   Apache Missile In-Flight Test Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Apache Missile In-Flight Test Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0306122194 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 3 Jun p 9 </F>
<F P=103> BR0306122194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Armament: The Apache Missile </F>
Flies"] 
  [Text] Two air-to-ground Apache missiles, developed by 
Matra-Defense, were carried for the first time under the wings 
of a German Tornado aircraft of the Luftwaffe. The Apache, a 
French version of the cruise missile, employs stealth technology 
and flies at a low altitude. Moreover, the Apache is equipped 
with navigation systems that allow exceptional precision 
targeting. The version ordered by the Luftwaffe and which is 
being developed in the framework of a 2.2-billion French franc 
[Fr] contract (with Fr600 million for adapting the missile) is 
the "antiship submunitions dispenser." The objective is to equip 
the 180 German Tornado planes with those missiles within the 
framework of a modernization program. The final contracts could 
then involve several billion French francs. 
  The development of the Apache, which was initiated in 1989, 
has reached the stage of in-flight testing. The French version, 
intended to be used by the Mirage 2000 D first and then by the 
Rafale, will be operational in 1997. Right now, Matra is 
planning to propose an even more effective version. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

